<HEADLINE>
EVA AIR LAUNCHES TAIPEI-SAIPAN SCHEDULED CHARTER FLIGHT SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April   3  (CNA) 04/03/07  18:53:07 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
Eva  Air, one  of Taiwan's  major international airlines,
launched a scheduled charter service Tuesday between Taipei and
Saipan -- the largest island in the Northern Marianas, a U.S.
Commonwealth territory in the West Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The airline will operate two non-stop charter flights between
Taipei and Saipan every week.
</P>
<P>
According to Eva Air, the flights will depart from Taipei at
10:30 p.m. every Tuesday and Saturday and land in Saipan four
hours later. They will take off from Saipan for the return trips
at 6:30 a.m. every Wednesday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Taipei-Saipan charter service will use an Airbus 330-200,
which seats 252 passengers, including 24 in business class
seating.
</P>
<P>
In celebration of the launch of the service, Eva Air will select
two lucky passengers from each flight between April 7 and April
17 through the drawing of lots and offer each of them a Nintendo
Wii game console.
</P>
<P>
Eva Air has indicated that it plans to operate the new direct
service for at least one year and then reassess market demand.
</P>
<P>
The airline previously served the Taipei-Saipan route with
charter flights in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new route is expected to bring more than 20,000 Taiwanese
tourists to the Northern Marianas each year.
</P>
